Federal Policing protects Canada, its people and its interests against today’s greatest domestic and international criminal threats, including risks related to national security, organized and transnational crime, financial crime and cybercrime.

We are Canada's national police service and a world-renowned institution. We are unique in that we police at the international, federal, provincial and municipal levels. Federal Policing is a core responsibility within the RCMP. We operate in every province and territory across the country, as well as internationally. Our organization of passionate and dedicated police officers and civilian employees are united in achieving one mission: to ensure the safety and security of Canadians.

Why choose a career with the RCMP? 
- Travel opportunities/adventure across Canada and around the world; 
- Access to over 150 specialized fields; 
- Training allowance and ongoing learning opportunities; 
- Competitive salary and benefits; 
- The chance to have a meaningful impact in your community and across the country.

Our Vision
The Alameda County Probation Department is committed to making our communities the safest in the nation.

Our Mission
To support and restore communities by providing compassionate supervision and accountability to justice-involved youth and adults, and provide preventive and rehabilitative services through evidence-based practices and collaborative partnerships.

Our Guiding Principles
We are committed to being an organization that:
- empowers staff and promotes respectful, forthright communication;
- engages collaboratively with our stakeholders and the community;
- promotes diversity and cultural awareness;
- embodies integrity and ethical conduct;
- uses research and data to inform practice;
- provides gender-responsive and trauma-informed care;
- strives for continuous process improvements through innovation driven by performance-based operations; and
- honors the belief that people can change

The LASPD employs 404 sworn police officers, 138 school safety officers (SSOs), and has 38 support personnel.  These dedicated men and women provide police services 24 hours a day/7days a week to over 900,000 students, 66,000 employees, over 1,342 schools and facilities spanning 710 square miles. 
 
The LASPD was established in 1948, and, over the last 60 years, has steadily grown and expanded the services provided to the LAUSD, which is the second largest school district in the United States.  The LASPD is the second largest school police department in the United States and the fourth largest police department in Los Angeles County.
 
The LASPD is committed to providing highly specialized police services that focus on creating a safe and tranquil environment for students and staff on school campuses, which enhance and facilitate the learning process.  In addition, the LASPD fosters partnerships and working relationships with parents, local businesses, community leaders, and the 15 outside law enforcement agencies to create safe passages for students to go to and from school.
 
In order to achieve this, the men and women of the LASPD provide police services with the following values:
·         Maintain the highest level of integrity and professionalism;
·         Respect individual rights and freedoms;
·         Consult with, and be responsible to the needs of the community;
·         Uphold the rule of law;
·         Be culturally sensitive;
·         Develop, mentor, and be responsible to the needs and welfare of all police staff through example and leadership.

The Military Veterans Wellness Program (MVWP) is a first of its kind program aimed to help improve the well-being of Canadian military veterans by providing law enforcement members with a better understanding of the issues veterans may be facing and providing them with the tools to help.

This program was developed in partnership with the Toronto Police Service - Community Partnership & Engagement Unit (CPEU), Department of National Defence (DND), Canadian Armed Forces (CAF), Veterans Affairs Canada (VAC), The Royal Canadian Legion (RCL), Operational Stress Injury Social Support (OSISS) and many others.

The MVWP training program is available free of charge on the Canadian Police Knowledge Network (CPKN) www.cpkn.ca/en/course/military-veterans-wellness-program. It provides an understanding about military culture, challenges transitioning to civilian life and mental and physical barriers. It also addresses how a veteran may begin having suicidal ideations, or living in a situation where they do not have a home and experience crisis. The MVWP is a complete program, which provides de-escalation training specific to a veteran in crisis, information about the national veteran social services and the mechanism to make a timely referral. The program will better equip law enforcement members to recognize veterans in crisis in their community and help them get access to the support they need. 

The projected outcomes include;
 Reducing the number of veterans living without a home and/or in mental health crisis;
 Providing dignity and prosperity for all our Canadian Armed Forces veterans;
 Increasing public safety in communities across Canada;
 Provide additional resources for law enforcement members for their own well-being.

For more information, please contact the National Program Coordinators at
TPSMilitaryWellness@TorontoPolice.on.ca

The United States Marshals Service (USMS) is a federal law enforcement agency within the U.S. Department of Justice (28 U.S.C. § 561). It is the oldest American federal law enforcement agency and was created by the Judiciary Act of 1789 during the presidency of George Washington as the Office of the United States Marshal.[3] The USMS as it stands today was established in 1969 to provide guidance and assistance to Marshals throughout the federal judicial districts. USMS is an agency of the United States executive branch reporting to the United States Attorney General, but serves as the enforcement arm of the United States federal courts to ensure the effective operation of the judiciary and integrity of the Constitution.

Special Deputy Marshals -
The Director of the United States Marshals Service is authorized to deputize the following persons to perform the functions of a Deputy U.S. Marshal in any district designated by the Director:
 (a) Selected officers or employees of the Department of Justice;
 (b) Selected federal, state, or local law enforcement officers whenever the law enforcement needs of the U.S. Marshals Service so require;
 (c) Selected employees of private security companies in providing courtroom security for the Federal judiciary;
 (d) Other persons designated by the Associate Attorney General pursuant to 28 CFR 0.19(a)(3).

The State Border Guard Service of Ukraine is charged with the tasks of ensuring inviolability of state borders and protection of sovereign rights of Ukraine within its exclusive (maritime) economic zone.



Principal functions of the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine



Principal functions of the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine are as follows:



policing Ukraine’s state border on land, sea, rivers, lakes, and other water bodies in order to prevent any illegal change of its line and to enforce the regime of the state border and the borderline regime;
exercising border control and allowing passage across the border, according to the established procedure, of individuals, vehicles, cargos and other properties as well as detecting and stopping illegal movement thereof;
safeguarding Ukraine’s sovereign rights in its exclusive (maritime) economic zone, and supervising the exercise of rights and the meeting of obligations in that zone by other states, Ukrainian and foreign legal and natural persons, and international organizations;
carrying out intelligence, information and analytical, and operational criminal investigation activities to ensure protection of Ukraine’s state border in accordance with the Law of Ukraine on Intelligence Bodies in Ukraine and the Law of Ukraine on Operational Criminal Investigation;
participating in the fight against organized crime and counteracting illegal migration at Ukraine’s state border as well as within the bounds of the border districts controlled;
participating in state protection of the places of permanent and temporary stay of the President of Ukraine and officials listed in the Law of Ukraine on State Protection of Public Authorities and Officials of Ukraine;
guarding Ukraine’s diplomatic institutions abroad;
coordinating the activities of military formations and relevant law-enforcement bodies related to protection of Ukraine’s state border as well as coordinating the activities of state bodies that exercise various types of control over crossing of Ukraine’s state border or take part in enforcement of the state border regime, the borderline regime, and the regime at Ukrainian state border checkpoints.


Basic operational principles

of the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine



Basic operational principles of the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine include:



legality;
respect for and observance of human and citizens’ rights and freedoms;
belonging to no party;
continuity;
combination of public, secret, and conspiratorial activity forms and methods;
sole command; collegiality in important decision-making;
interaction with public authorities, local governments, and community organizations when fulfilling the tasks vested in the State Border Service of Ukraine;
openness for democratic civilian control.
 (In accordance with the Law of Ukraine

on the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine)

